properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Buldah, Chandlers Creek.

  • There is a bushfire near the Monaro Highway in Rockton, NSW that is not yet under control.
  • The fire is travelling in a south-easterly direction and could travel over the Monaro Highway, close to the Victorian border.
  • For information on the Taskers fire in Rockton, NSW, visit https://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/fire-information/fires-near-me
  • This Advice message replaces the Advice issued at 1:20pm Tuesday 19 September.
There is currently no threat to communities, but you should continue to stay informed and monitor conditions.
What you should do: 
  • Monitor weather conditions and warnings. 
  • Review your fire survival plan. 
  • If you do not have a plan, decide what you will do if the situation changes.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Firefighters are responding to this fire.
  • Smoke will be visible from nearby communities and roads. 
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

The next update is expected by 20/09/2023 09:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Advice message is being issued for Simpsons Creek and surrounds.

  • There is a grassfire at Princes Hwy, Simpsons Creek that is not yet under control.
  • Fire and smoke are on both sides of the Highway. 
  • Firefighters will be in attendance overnight.
  • This Advice message replaces the Advice issued at 7:40pm Tuesday 19 September.   
There is currently no threat to you, but you should stay informed and monitor conditions.
What you should do: 
  • Keep the roads clear so emergency services can respond.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Visit https://traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/ for traffic impacts to the Princes Highway. 
  • Smoke will be visible from nearby communities and roads. 
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

The next update is expected by 20/09/2023 09:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires)

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice is being issued for Mallacoota, Chandlers Creek and surrounds.
  • Smoke from fires in NSW is travelling into Victoria.
  • There is currently no threat to Victorian communities but you should stay informed and monitor conditions. 
  • For information on the Taskers fire in Rockton, NSW, visit https://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/fire-information/fires-near-me
  • This Advice message replaces the Advice issued at 3:00pm Tuesday 19 September.
Smoke can affect people's health. You should be aware of the health impacts of smoke on you and others.
What you should do:

  • There is currently no action required, however, if you are travelling, consider not travelling over the border into NSW. Instead, it is recommended to travel west towards Cann River. 
  • Your nose is an excellent smoke detector. If you can smell smoke, take the necessary precautions to protect your health. You can self-assess the air quality near you using: https://www.epa.vic.gov.au/for-community/environmental-information/air-quality/smoke/smoke-your-health.
Take action to reduce your exposure to smoke and protect your health: 
  • People more sensitive to smoke are those with a heart or lung condition, including asthma; people over the age of 65 years; infants and children; and pregnant women. 
  • If you are sensitive to smoke, limit prolonged or heavy physical activity. Where possible, try to stay indoors. 
  • If you have a heart or lung conditions, take your medication as prescribed by your doctor. 
  • If you are asthmatic, follow your asthma plan and carry reliever medication with you. 
  • For more information on smoke and your health, visit the Better Health Channel. If you are concerned about symptoms, call Nurse on Call on 1300 606 024 or see your doctor. 
  • If you or anyone in your care has trouble breathing or tightness in the chest, call Triple Zero (000) for an ambulance.
Impacts in your area:
  • You may see or smell smoke in these areas.
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

The next update is expected by 20/09/2023 09:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
